{"title_page": "Siege of Ansi", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Siege of Ansi\n| image       = Tang-Korean wars.png\n| caption     = Map showing the invasion of Tang forces to Goguryeo\n| partof      = the [[First campaign in the Goguryeo\u2013Tang War]]\n| date        = 20 June\u201318 September 645 CE\n| place       = [[Ansi City|Ansi]]\n| result      = [[Goguryeo]] victory\n| combatant1  = [[Goguryeo]]\n| combatant2  = [[Tang dynasty|Tang]]\n| commander1  = [[Yang Manchun]]<br/>Go yeon-su{{POW}}<br/>Go hye-jin{{POW}}\n| commander2  = [[Emperor Taizong of Tang]]<br/>[[Li Shiji]]<br/>[[Zhangsun Wuji]]<br/>[[Li Daozong]]{{WIA}}<br/>[[Xue Rengui]] <!-- commanders are not anyone in command of a sub-unit -->\n| strength1   = ~5,000 (garrison) <br/>~150,000 (enforcement troops)<br/>\n| strength2   = ~30,000 soldiers\n| casualties1 = 20,000+ killed <br/> 36,800 surrendered<ref name=gr02-197>{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=David|title=Medieval Chinese Warfare 300\u2013900|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553532|page=197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpmBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA197#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=28 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n| casualties2 = about 2,000\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=Korean name\n|tablewidth=315\n|color=lightsteelblue\n|hangul={{linktext|\uc548\uc2dc\uc131| \uc804\ud22c}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u5b89\u5e02\u57ce| \u6230\u9b2a}}\n|rr = Ansiseong jeontu\n| mr = Anshis\u014fng ch\u014fnt'u\n}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Ansi''' was a battle between [[Goguryeo]] and [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] forces in [[Ansi City|Ansi]], a fortress in the [[Liaodong Peninsula]], and the culmination of the [[First campaign in the Goguryeo\u2013Tang War]]. The confrontation lasted for about 3 months from 20 June 645 to 18 September 645. \n\nThe initial phase of combat resulted in the defeat of a Gorguryeo relief force of 150,000 and resulted in the Tang troops laying siege to the fortress. After a siege lasting around 2 months, the Tang forces constructed a rampart with 500,000 troops and laborers. However, the rampart was on the brink of completion, when a section of it collapsed and was taken over by the defenders. This, along with arriving Goguryeo reinforcements and the lack of supplies, forced Tang troops into a retreat. Over 20,000 Goguryeo troops and 180,000 Tang troops were killed during the siege.\n\n==Background==\nIn the year 644, Taizu of Tang decided to invade Goguryeo in the face of opposition inside the Tang Dynasty. The assassination of Yongnu of Goguryeo and other officials by Yeon Gaesomun was used to justify invasion. For the next year, he began preparations for an invasion, preparing troops, ships, and siege engines, and conducting reconnissance. On the 1st of April 645, under the pretext of marching to camp Huaiyuan, Tang forces led by [[Li Shiji]] suddenly turned to invade [[Goguryeo]].<ref name=\"\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c2\">{{cite web|url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0034848|title=\ubbfc\uc871\ubb38\ud654\ub300\ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804- \uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c|website=encykorea|language=Korean|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> They attacked several castles including [[Fushun|Shin]] and [[Gaizhou|Geonan]], to throw the defense system of Goguryeo into disarray. The plan failed, and [[Li Shiji]] instead arrayed all Tang forces to besiege [[Shenyang|Gaemo]] on 15 April. Gaemo fell on 25 April. Simultaneously, naval forces led by [[Zhang Liang (Tang dynasty)|Zhang Liang]] had landed in [[Liaodong Peninsula]] and went on to capture [[Dalian|Bisa]] on the 2nd of May. Meanwhile, [[Emperor Taizong of Tang]] joined the forces and they captured [[Liaoyang|Yodong]] and [[Dengta|Baegam]] one after another.<ref name=\"\u5b89\u5e02\u57ce\" />\n\nAfterwards, the Tang forces decided to attack Ansi Fortress, a fortress-city with a population of around 100,000, invading the fortress on 20 June. Texts of the Joseon Dynasty describe the name of the chief of Ansi Fortress was said to be Yang Manchun.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?cid=47306&docId=3560134&categoryId=47306|title=\uc548\uc2dc\uc131 \uc2f8\uc6c0|website=terms.naver.com|language=ko|accessdate=2020-02-06}}</ref> In response to the Tang invasion, [[Yeon Gaesomun]], Generalissimo of Goguryeo, sent about 150,000 forces with [[Go yeon-su]] and [[Go hye-jin]] to rescue Ansi.<ref name=\"\u5b89\u5e02\u57ce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doopedia.co.kr/doopedia/master/master.do?_method=view&MAS_IDX=101013000762430|title=\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc2f8\uc6c0[\u5b89\u5e02\u57ce\u2500] - \ub450\ud53c\ub514\uc544|language=Korean|website=doopedia.co.kr|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n===The battle to rescue Ansi===\nOn 20 July, the two sides descended into battle. The Tang Dynasty sent [[Li Shiji]] leading 15,000 infantry and cavalry to fight the Goguryeo army directly. But Tang general [[Zhangsun Wuji]] led 11,000 elite cavalry across the canyon from the north of the mountain to hit the rear of Goguryeo forces. In the battle, Taizong personally led 4,000 infantry and cavalry to fight. The Tang army came out victorious in the end, decimating the Goguryeo forces. At least 20,000 Goguryeo soldiers were killed and 36,800 Goguryeo soldiers, including their generals Go Yeonsu and Go Hyezin, surrendered. The Tang army captured 50,000 horses, over 50,000 cattle, and over 10,000 iron armors. After the battle, Tang had succeeded in isolating Ansi fortress from other Goguryeo territory.<ref name=gr02-197>{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=David|title=Medieval Chinese Warfare 300\u2013900|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553532|page=197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpmBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA197#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=28 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Assault on the Ansi fortress===\nThe Tang first attacked Ansi Fortress with several siege weapons including catapults and battering rams. However Goguryeo repelled the attacks and repaired the ramparts each time. As a result, Taizong was furious and Li Shi asked permission to massacre all the men and women if the fortress was captured, which was granted. After Anshi people heard this, they defended the fortress more tenaciously, the Tang army's assaults were repelled several times. When the Ansi fortress attack came to a standstill, Tang was in a hurry so the Tang Army attacked the west side of the fortress as many as six or seven times per day.<ref name=\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c>{{cite web|url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0034848|title=\ubbfc\uc871\ubb38\ud654\ub300\ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804- \uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c|language=Korean|website=encykorea|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> One night, hundreds of Goguryeo soldiers climbed out of the fortress and attempted to attack the Tang army. When Taizong heard about it, he called up soldiers to make an emergency joint attack which killed dozens of Goguryeo\u00a0soldiers, and the rest fled back to the fortress.<ref name=\"\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db\" />\n\nThe Tang forces grew weary and considered the idea of bypassing Ansi fortress to attack other parts of Goguryeo, which was rejected due to threat Ansi posed to the advancing Tang forces.<ref name=\"gr02-197\" /> Under the leadership of Tang's prince Li Daozong, Tang forces attempted to build a rampart in the southeastern corner of the fortress, gradually approaching the wall. Meanwhile, the external wall was constantly raised by the garrison. Li Daozong was injured in the battle. The Tang used 500,000 laborers and soldiers to build the rampart and the top of the rampart was only a few feet away from the fortress.<ref name=\"\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.gushiwen.org/guwen/bookv_647.aspx|title=\u8d44\u6cbb\u901a\u9274\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db_\u53e4\u8bd7\u6587\u7f51|website=m.gushiwen.org|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref> It overlooked the city. Fu Fuai, one commander of the Tang Army, stationed his troops on the top of the rampart. However, Fu Fuai left the camp privately and the rampart suddenly fell, and the Goguryeo army occupied it. Taizong was very angry and put Fu Fuai to death. After that, Tang tried to regain the rampart for 3 days but failed. On the 3rd day, the Goguryeo army reinforcements arrived and Taizong had still not captured the Ansi Fortress. In addition, the weather was getting colder and food ran out, so the Tang unavoidably ordered retreat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?docId=918153&cid=42957&categoryId=42957|title=\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc2f8\uc6c0|language=Korean|website=terms.naver.com|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> Taizong's retreat was difficult and many of his soldiers died.<ref name=\"Graff198\">{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=David|title=Medieval Chinese Warfare 300\u2013900|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553532|page=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpmBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=3 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Taizong himself tended to the injuries of his Turkic generals [[Qibi Heli]] and [[Ashina Simo]], who were both wounded during the campaign against Goguryeo.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qTm6Yka5GigC&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false Skaff 2012], p. 95.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Tang Dynasty estimated that about 2,000 Tang soldiers were killed per day during the 3 month long siege period and the Tang Army lost an estimated 8,000 war horses. This adds up to around 180,000 Tang troops killed during the siege, in addition to the troops killed during the retreat. Taizong thought he could not win the war meanwhile, feeling deeply sorry in the end.<ref name=\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db/> In 645, Emperor Taizong founded the [[Fayuan Temple|Minzhong Temple]], the oldest temple in Beijing, to commemorate his soldiers who died in Goguryeo.<ref name=\"museum\">{{cite web|title=Record of Restoring the Buddha Relic at Minzhong Temple|url=http://museum.sinica.edu.tw/exhibition_item.php?id=2&item=397&lang=en-us|website=Museum of the Institute of History and Philology|publisher=Academia Sinica|quote=The Minzhong Temple is known today as the Fayuan Temple in Beijing. The temple was built by Emperor Li Shimin to mourn and salvage the lost souls in his failed attempt to conquer Goguryeo.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haw|first1=Stephen G.|title=Beijing \u2013 A Concise History|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134150335|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J8J8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Perkins|first1=Dorothy|title=Encyclopedia of China: History and Culture|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135935696|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tsIeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT112#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Jaivin|first1=Linda|title=Beijing|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=9781780233000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SJAOBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT23#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Emperor Taizong prepared another invasion in 648, but died, possibly due to an illness he contracted during his Goguryeo campaigns.<ref name=\"Wei\">{{cite book|last1=Chen|first1=Jack Wei|title=The Poetics of Sovereignty: On Emperor Taizong of the Tang Dynasty|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674056084|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wlDivOQGakC&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=4 August 2016|language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe Goguryeo forces lost over 20,000 people, with over 36,800 troops being taken prisoner during the early stage of combat. The casualties of the Goruryeo troops during the siege itself are unknown.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c2\" />\n\nTensions between Goguryeo and Tang continued, until Goguryeo was finally defeated by a joint Silla-Tang force in the year 668.<ref name=\"gr02-197\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe 2018 South Korean film ''[[The Great Battle (film)|The Great Battle]]'' is based on this siege.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/|title=Yonhap News Agency|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ansi, Siege Of}}\n[[Category:Battles involving the Tang dynasty]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Goguryeo]]\n[[Category:645]]\n[[Category:640s conflicts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Siege of Ansi\n| image       = Tang-Korean wars.png\n| caption     = Map showing the invasion of Tang forces to Goguryeo\n| partof      = the [[First campaign in the Goguryeo\u2013Tang War]]\n| date        = 20 June\u201318 September 645 CE\n| place       = [[Ansi City|Ansi]]\n| result      = [[Goguryeo]] victory\n| combatant1  = [[Goguryeo]]\n| combatant2  = [[Tang dynasty|Tang]]\n| commander1  = [[Yang Manchun]]<br/>Go yeon-su{{POW}}<br/>Go hye-jin{{POW}}\n| commander2  = [[Emperor Taizong of Tang]]<br/>[[Li Shiji]]<br/>[[Zhangsun Wuji]]<br/>[[Li Daozong]]{{WIA}}<br/>[[Xue Rengui]] <!-- commanders are not anyone in command of a sub-unit -->\n| strength1   = ~5,000 (garrison) <br/>~150,000 (enforcement troops)<br/>\n| strength2   = ~30,000 soldiers\n| casualties1 = 20,000+ killed <br/> 36,800 surrendered<ref name=gr02-197>{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=David|title=Medieval Chinese Warfare 300\u2013900|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553532|page=197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpmBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA197#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=28 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n| casualties2 = about 18,000\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=Korean name\n|tablewidth=315\n|color=lightsteelblue\n|hangul={{linktext|\uc548\uc2dc\uc131| \uc804\ud22c}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u5b89\u5e02\u57ce| \u6230\u9b2a}}\n|rr = Ansiseong jeontu\n| mr = Anshis\u014fng ch\u014fnt'u\n}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Ansi''' was a battle between [[Goguryeo]] and [[Tang dynas