Daozong was injured in the battle. The Tang used 500,000 laborers and soldiers to build the rampart and the top of the rampart was only a few feet away from the fortress.<ref name=\"\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.gushiwen.org/guwen/bookv_647.aspx|title=\u8d44\u6cbb\u901a\u9274\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db_\u53e4\u8bd7\u6587\u7f51|website=m.gushiwen.org|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref> It overlooked the city. Fu Fuai, one commander of the Tang Army, stationed his troops on the top of the rampart. However, Fu Fuai left the camp privately and the rampart suddenly fell, and the Goguryeo army occupied it. Taizong was very angry and put Fu Fuai to death. After that, Tang tried to regain the rampart for 3 days but failed. On the 3rd day, the Goguryeo army reinforcements arrived and Taizong had still not captured the Ansi Fortress. In addition, the weather was getting colder and food ran out, so the Tang unavoidably ordered retreat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?docId=918153&cid=42957&categoryId=42957|title=\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc2f8\uc6c0|language=Korean|website=terms.naver.com|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> Taizong's retreat was difficult and many of his soldiers died.<ref name=\"Graff198\">{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=David|title=Medieval Chinese Warfare 300\u2013900|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553532|page=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpmBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=3 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Taizong himself tended to the injuries of his Turkic generals [[Qibi Heli]] and [[Ashina Simo]], who were both wounded during the campaign against Goguryeo.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qTm6Yka5GigC&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false Skaff 2012], p. 95.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Tang Dynasty estimated that about 2,000 Tang soldiers were killed per day during the 3 month long siege period and the Tang Army lost an estimated 8,000 war horses. This adds up to around 180,000 Tang troops killed during the siege, in addition to the troops killed during the retreat. Taizong thought he could not win the war meanwhile, feeling deeply sorry in the end.<ref name=\u5510\u7eaa\u00b7\u5510\u7eaa\u5341\u56db/> In 645, Emperor Taizong founded the [[Fayuan Temple|Minzhong Temple]], the oldest temple in Beijing, to commemorate his soldiers who died in Goguryeo.<ref name=\"museum\">{{cite web|title=Record of Restoring the Buddha Relic at Minzhong Temple|url=http://museum.sinica.edu.tw/exhibition_item.php?id=2&item=397&lang=en-us|website=Museum of the Institute of History and Philology|publisher=Academia Sinica|quote=The Minzhong Temple is known today as the Fayuan Temple in Beijing. The temple was built by Emperor Li Shimin to mourn and salvage the lost souls in his failed attempt to conquer Goguryeo.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haw|first1=Stephen G.|title=Beijing \u2013 A Concise History|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134150335|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J8J8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Perkins|first1=Dorothy|title=Encyclopedia of China: History and Culture|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135935696|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tsIeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT112#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Jaivin|first1=Linda|title=Beijing|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=9781780233000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SJAOBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT23#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Emperor Taizong prepared another invasion in 648, but died, possibly due to an illness he contracted during his Goguryeo campaigns.<ref name=\"Wei\">{{cite book|last1=Chen|first1=Jack Wei|title=The Poetics of Sovereignty: On Emperor Taizong of the Tang Dynasty|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674056084|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wlDivOQGakC&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=4 August 2016|language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe Goguryeo forces lost over 20,000 people, with over 36,800 troops being taken prisoner during the early stage of combat. The casualties of the Goruryeo troops during the siege itself are unknown.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"\uc548\uc2dc\uc131\uc804\ud22c2\" />\n\nTensions between Goguryeo and Tang continued, until Goguryeo was finally defeated by a joint Silla-Tang force in the year 668.<ref name=\"gr02-197\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe 2018 South Korean film ''[[The Great Battle (film)|The Great Battle]]'' is based on this siege.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/|title=Yonhap News Agency|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ansi, Siege Of}}\n[[Category:Battles involving the Tang dynasty]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Goguryeo]]\n[[Category:645]]\n[[Category:640s conflicts]]\n", "name_user": "Baturu1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Ansi"}
